The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Nov. 26: The government has fixed a price band of Rs 135-140 per share for Shipping Corporation of Indias (SCI) follow-on offer, shipping minister G.K. Vasan said. The offer will fetch about Rs 1,200 crore if fully subscribed at the upper level of the band. The government will dilute a 10 per cent stake in SCI, while the company will issue fresh equity amounting to 10 per cent of the paid-up capital.                            
	 Mumbai, Nov. 26: Market regulator Sebi today said the corporate and government debt limits would be auctioned among the FIIs next month, following a decision to permit them to pump in more money in these papers.                             
	 Lisbon, Nov. 26: Portugal approved its 2011 austerity budget today, vowing to spur growth and apply tough spending cuts as it seeks to avoid an Irish-style bailout. Prime Minister Jose Socrates said the budgets passage removed Portugal from the crosshairs of the euro zone crisis.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 26: Drug maker Claris Lifesciences today lowered the price band of its Rs 300-crore initial public offer to Rs 228-235 per share because of poor response from investors, while extending the closing date to December 2.                             
	 Mumbai, Nov. 26: The initial public offer of Manganese Ore (India) Ltd (MOIL), was subscribed 0.76 times on the first day of the issue today, generating a demand worth Rs 953 crore.                            
	 New York, Nov. 26: Kohlberg Kravis Roberts amp; Co will buy Del Monte Foods Co in a deal worth about $4 billion, excluding debt.                             
	 New Delhi, Nov. 26: The income tax department has struck an estimated Rs 50-crore deal with BSNL to provide 51,000 mobile connections and 1,000 high-end BlackBerry phones for secure and fast communication among its officers and staff.
                                                                                                                          
